      • recover

        public ResultVoid recover​(Function<Throwable,​ResultVoid> f)
        Description copied from interface: ResultVoid
        Attempts to restore an error ResultVoid to a success.

        When the Result is already a success, then the result is returned unmodified.

        
 void doSomethingRisky(String s) throws Exception {...}
 ResultVoid result = Result.ofVoid(() -> doSomethingRisky("first"))
                           .recover(e -> Result.ofVoid(() -> doSomethingRisky("second")));
        Specified by:
        recover in interface ResultVoid
        Parameters:
        f - the function to recover from the error
        Returns:
        if Result is an error, a new Result, either a Success, or if recovery is not possible another error. If the Result is already a success, then this returns itself.

        Description copied from interface: ResultVoid
        A handler for success states.

 void handleSuccess() {...}

        public void onError​(Consumer<Throwable> errorConsumer)
        Description copied from interface: BaseResult
        A handler for error states.

        If the Result is an error, then supply the error to the Consumer. Does nothing if the Result is a success.

        When this is an error then tne Consumer will be supplied with the error. When this is a success, then nothing happens.

       .onError(e -> handleError(e));
        Specified by:

      • onError

        public <E extends Throwable> ResultVoid onError​(Class<E> errorClass,
                                                Consumer<E> consumer)
        Description copied from interface: ResultVoid
        A handler for error state, when the error matches the errorClass.

        If the `Result` is an error and that error is an instance of the errorClass, then supply the error to the `Consumer`. Does nothing if the error is not an instance of the errorClass, or is a success.

        Similar to the catch block in a try-catch.

        
 void handleError(UnsupportedOperationException e) {...}
 Result.of(() -> getValue())
       .onError(UnsupportedOperationException.class,
                e -> handleError(e))
        Specified by:
        onError in interface ResultVoid
        Type Parameters:
        E - the Type of the Throwable to match
        Parameters:
        errorClass - the class of Throwable to match
        consumer - the consumer to call if it matches
        Returns:
        the original unmodified Result
